%I A396111 #29 Jun 17 2026 19:04:38
%S A396111 0,1,1,4,4,9,9,1,16,6,4,13,11,22,20,2,31,11,7,22,18,35,31,3,46,16,10,
%T A396111 31,25,48,42,4,61,21,13,40,32,61,53,5,76,26,16,49,39,74,64,6,91,31,19,
%U A396111 58,46,87,75,7,106,36,22,67,53,100,86,8,121,41,25,76,60,113
%N A396111 a(n) = n^4 mod (2*n+1).
%C A396111 This is also a sequence of the form ((n+1)^p - n^p) mod (2*n+1). One can prove that when p is even such sequences match A000004 (all zeros), but when p is odd they match n^(p-1) mod (2*n+1). Expressions (n+1)^p - n^p are the nexus numbers of order p (but Eric Weisstein indexes them with p-1). This sequence is obtained with p=5.
%C A396111 Conjecture: a(n) contains every nonnegative integer k at least once (tested up to k=600000).
%C A396111 True because a(8*k-1) = k for all k >= 1. - _Robert Israel_, Jun 11 2026
%C A396111 Conjecture: a(n) contains every integer k only a finite number of times.
%C A396111 True because 2*n+1 divides 16*a(n)-1. - _Robert Israel_, Jun 11 2026
%D A396111 J. H. Conway and R. K. Guy, The Book of Numbers, New York: Springer-Verlag, 1996.
%H A396111 Stanislav Sykora, <a href="/A396111/b396111.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..2000</a>
%H A396111 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/NexusNumber.html">Nexus Number</a>.
%F A396111 a(n) = A022521(n) mod (2*n+1).
%e A396111 a(5) = 9 because (5^4 mod (2*5+1)) = 9, and also ((6^5-5^5) mod (2*5+1)) = 9
%p A396111 seq(n^4 mod (2*n+1), n = 0 .. 100); # _Robert Israel_, Jun 11 2026
%t A396111 a[n_] := Mod[n^4, 2*n+1]; Array[a, 70, 0] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Jun 01 2026 *)
%o A396111 (PARI) a(n)=((n+1)^5-n^5)%(2*n+1)
%o A396111 (PARI) a(n)=n^4%(2*n+1)
%o A396111 (Python)
%o A396111 def A396111(n): return pow(n,4,2*n+1) # _Chai Wah Wu_, May 31 2026
%Y A396111 Cf. A123684 (p=3).
%Y A396111 Cf. A000583, A022521.
